Wage Determination
In this framework, for a worker to meet w/ another firm, the worker has to endure the cost of unemployment. Similarly, for the firm, losing a worker would imply waiting for another worker by incurring the vacancy cost. Thus, the matched worker and firm are in a bilateral monopoly situation.
Here we assume that the surplus is split by the level of wage that solves the following maximization problem: \[\begin{equation}
\max_{w}\left(\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)-U\left(t\right)\right)^{\gamma}\left(\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)-V\left(t\right)\right)^{1-\gamma}\label{eq:nash}
\end{equation}\] where \(\gamma\in\left(0,1\right)\). The functions \(\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)\) and \(\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)\)are the values of employed workers and a matched firm, here we make it explicit that only \(w\) in this period can move. The solution to this problem is often called Generalized Nash Bargaining Rule.
The functions \(\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)\) and \(\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)\) can be written as: \[\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)=w\Delta+\frac{1}{1+r\Delta}\left(\left(1-\sigma\Delta\right)W\left(t+\Delta\right)+\sigma\Delta U\left(t+\Delta\right)\right)\] and \[\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)=p\left(t\right)\Delta-w\Delta+\frac{1}{1+r\Delta}\left(\sigma\Delta V\left(t+\Delta\right)+\left(1-\sigma\Delta\right)J\left(t+\Delta\right)\right).\]
By taking FOC for [eq:nash], we have: \[\begin{align*}
\max_{w} & \gamma\ln\left(\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)-U\left(t\right)\right)+\left(1-\gamma\right)\ln\left(\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)-V\left(t\right)\right)\\
0 & =\frac{\gamma}{\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)-U\left(t\right)}\frac{\partial\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)}{\partial w}+\frac{1-\gamma}{\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)-V\left(t\right)}\frac{\partial\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)}{\partial w}
\end{align*}\]
Given \(\frac{\partial\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)}{\partial w}=\Delta,\frac{\partial\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)}{\partial w}=-\Delta\), we have \[\begin{align}
0 & =\frac{\gamma}{\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)-U\left(t\right)}\Delta-\frac{1-\gamma}{\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)-V\left(t\right)}\Delta\nonumber \\
0 & =\frac{\gamma}{\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)-U\left(t\right)}-\frac{1-\gamma}{\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)-V\left(t\right)}\nonumber \\
\frac{1-\gamma}{\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)-V\left(t\right)} & =\frac{\gamma}{\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)-U\left(t\right)}\nonumber \\
\left(1-\gamma\right)\left(\tilde{W}\left(w,t\right)-U\left(t\right)\right) & =\gamma\left(\tilde{J}\left(w,t\right)-V\left(t\right)\right)\label{eq:foc}
\end{align}\]
so the \(w^{*}\)that satisfies [eq:foc] is the eq. wage.
